Rating: 4
I didn't have the balsamic vinegar, ran down to the corner grocer and bought what they had on the shelf, raspberry vinegar. I used powdered cinnamon because that is what I had on hand. It hasn't even cooled yet and I had to review this recipe because it tastes so wonderfully intense with a lot of depth. After an initial taste using 3/4 c. sugar, I increased it to the amount called for because the raw organic sugar I was using seemed to taste more mildly sweet than white sugar. I used a liberal amount of vinegar adding a little at a time until the flavors tasted balanced. I can't wait to try it with turkey at Christmas!

Rating: 4
Oh my Lawt!!! This is hands down the BEST cranberry sauce EVER!!! Following the advice of a few Master foodies, I cut the sugar in half. To that the Good Idea Fairy prompted me to add 1/4 c. of Grand Marnier & a few tablespoons of tawny port...et VOILA!!!! Fabulosity on a spoon!!! My 15 year old initially turned his nose up at it when I offered him a taste. He changed his tune as soon as it hit his bottom lip. After cleaning the spoon he asked to clean the pot once it cooled. W00T!!!

Rating: 4
This is the best cranberry sauce I've ever made or tasted! I've been making it since the recipe came out in the 2008 Gourmet issue, and people always ask me for the recipe. This year, I made it with only 1/2 cup of sugar, instead of the 11/4 cups, and I prefer the tartness, though it's still sweet enough from the dates and OJ.

Rating: 4
I followed the suggestions of some other reviewers and reduced the sugar to 1/2 cup. However, I found this almost too tart so at the end I added some honey and chopped sugared apples slices. I also added about 1T fresh ground ginger and used Blood Orange balsamic vinegar. I did not have dates so substituted white raisins and dried cherries. Finally I added about 1/2-3/4 c chopped walnuts after the sauce had sat a bit.

